A POP IN THE CORN

We enjoyed Convocation. We didn’t enjoy the lines, the score
of the football game. the early ending of a rather undanceable
Dance, or having Saga workers and Requiem people miss many

events.

But for most people, most 01 the time, there was something

to learn, to amuse. to move.

Convocation knocked Grinnell off its usual apathetic strlde. ‘

Students reacted to the change. The Peace‘Raliy was an exciting
successr Offrcampus parties ﬂourished. We lived a different life

. . r for three days.

in a week or so, Convocation will just be a memory: I heard
this one, talked to that one, got drunk with the other.

It was it oneshot thing. A big pop in the corn.

We’d better get back to the books . . .

A STUDENT OPINION

ENLIGHTENMENT FROM OONVO

By HERBERT U. PEGUES

one historian has said, “it is
historical fact as well as bio-
logical theory that the past—of
ten the distant past—lives on in
the present."

This resounding idea hung
over the heads of hundreds this
past weekend. Some ignored it;
to others it was a shocking re-
ality, and still others, a true
awareness

The historical links were put
beinre you so plainly. i need
not repeat the slavery of the
Negro and countless injustices
toward him for some 348 years.
These in a nutshell are facts
that have bred the forms of
racial uproar in America to
hay.

This is why the Negro thinks
the way he thinks, this is why
he lives the way he does, and
this is why he revolts the way

he does. Hopefully you know
all Americans, both black and
white, suffer the consequences
oi past and present "America
the free."

Admittedly. there are some
redeeming tactors. We can 0v»
ercome the grim historical re~
minders, or at least lessen
their severity, by reevaluating
our value system. Salvation
lies in your own mind. Wisdom
is a wonderful thing.

out in all your getting, you
must get understanding. All of
you really needed those racial.
1y oriented topics or the Con-
vocation, if just for peace of
mind. The intellectual Grinnell,
with the rest of America, can-
not rise above itself without un-
derstanding, the God — given
rights of all humanity. All men
are equal, as human beings,
under the sun.

