no the Editort’

I would like to comment
briefly on Mr. Marquardt's and
Mr. Tice‘s column in the Oct.
27 5&3. They refer to the seven
required courses envisioned in
the Curriculum Report as “lec-
ture courses.”

Even a hasty reading of the
report indicates, in my opinion,
that most required courses
would be taught in small sec-
tions, The proposed Humanities
course, for example, would
continue the work of the pres-
ent one, which is now taught
in sections averaging 18 stu-
dents. Emphasis in this course
is on literary analysis in depth
through the frequent writing of
papers which are thoroughly
criticized by the instructor,
and through conferences. (1
can testify that l have had stu~
dents in that course who ap-
proached literature in greater
depth than did some juniors
and seniors; hence I would
never call the course vague
and impersonal.)

Likewise the language cours-
es envisioned in the report (as
those now taught) would be of-
fered in small sections; and
the Social Studies and Humani-
ties In (Fine Arts) course!
would also involve work done
in sections.

1 am not here defending the
specific proposals of the re-
port; but I thought it might be
usetul to have someone not
connected with the committee
point out what seems to be a
factual inaccuracy in the col-
umn of Mr. Marquardt and Mr.
Tice.

Andrew P. Pebickl
