ANIMAL BEHAVIOUR

By Neil Fitch!

Conscientious administrators and functionaries are constantly
doing their duties here at Grinneil.

They protect college property from misuse and abuse

They keep the college running . . . like water , . . m‘ It ,
machine

Their public relations techniques for improving the Grinnell
image are timeless and without measure.

Someday I’d like to swing a column in their praises. But this
week they ought to be cut down.

Somewhere in the midst of their concern for college prop-
erty and their concern for Grinnell P.R.. they have lost nil
concern for the general welfare of the students who live here.

Convocauon offered a case or two in point:

Now it's nice to feed all the trustees on time. and it's nice to
make a good impression on the alumni.

But it‘s even nicer to reed Saga workers, and It the Quad
that simply didn’t happen during Super Weekend.

"By the time we had time to eat." one Quad waiter told me,
"all that was left were a few stale Danish pastries, I had to miss
three meals straight so I could help lat alums feed their faces.”

One hell of a lot of Saga workers and Verdi Requiem par.
formers were finagied into weekend work and rehearsal scheduler
precluding any benefit from Convocation.

“Martin Luther King got to see more of Grinneli Convocation
than i did," a student Requiem singer stated, “and he was only
here a few hours,"

Said another Quad worker. “Some girls worked breakfast all
morning. were given a whole half-hour for I break, and then had
to work lunch for two hours"

Lack of admirdstrative concern for student welfare, horr-
ovtr, isn’t just an accident or one busy weekend.

About two weeks ago, Cleveland freshman Louise Peick had
the misfortune to trip and cut the side of her head open in the
Forum music room.

Witnesses said they thought she was about to go into shock,
In they made her lie down on the floor.

And we all know what happens when you lie down on the
floor in the Forum.

Immediately the forces of concern (for college property, that
in) surged into action

The "Forum Lady" -— that is to say. the lady who work:
the desk and makes people keep their shoes on and sit up straight
(the epithet has the same connotation as "Avon Lady" or “Fullei
Brush Man”) — instantly arrived to console Louise.

Quoth the “Forum Lady," according to one witness:

“I’m sorry you cut your head open, but could you please
try not to bleed on my carpet?”

Quoih Louise: “I really wasn’t thinking about where I was
bleeding at the time.” ’

I understand that college telephone operators are just it little
busier these days than they were at the beginning of November
last year.

They are busy because they are still looking up telephone
numbers for students.

They are still looking up telephone numbers for students
because the Herd Books haven’t been printed yet.

”Why haven’t the Herd Books been 11th yet?” you
nsk. “Why aren‘t the new 1937-68 analogues out yet?”

Well, yoii know. I’d ask Mrsr Prescott over in Public Rela-
tions about that, but I’m afraid she‘s still a little tired from
pumping out Convocation schedules, Convocation programs. Com
vocation booklets, and Convocation news releases.

But now that Super Weekend is bagged, maybe she can work
I little on something to help students here —like a catalogue or I
herd book.

Now that the slums are gone, maybe Sage will have time
to feed Saga workers too.

Now that the college is a college again and not just I
convocation cluster, maybe it can begin looking out for its
college students.

Anyway, if you crntlr your skull in the Forum try to keep
your blood off the carpet, will you? Because they’ll probably
raise my tuition to pay 3er for cleaning it up.

